              <h2>How this simple loan calculator works</h2>
              <p>
                This calculator models a fixed-rate installment loan, such as a
                personal loan, auto loan, or debt consolidation loan. You choose
                the loan amount, interest rate, term, and payment frequency, and
                it computes:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>Payment per period (monthly, bi-weekly, weekly, etc.)</li>
                <li>Total number of payments</li>
                <li>Total interest paid over the life of the loan</li>
                <li>Total amount repaid (principal + interest)</li>
                <li>Estimated payoff time and effective APR</li>
                <li>
                  A full amortization schedule with principal and interest
                  breakdown
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h3>Formula for payment on a standard amortizing loan</h3>
              <p>
                For a fixed-rate loan with compounding each payment period, the
                payment is:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p>Let:</p>
                <ul>
                  <li>\( P \) = loan principal (amount borrowed)</li>
                  <li>
                    \( r \) = periodic interest rate (annual rate / payments per
                    year)
                  </li>
                  <li>\( n \) = total number of payments</li>
                </ul>
                <p>Then the payment per period \( A \) is:</p>
                <p>\[ A = P \cdot \frac{r(1+r)^n}{(1+r)^n - 1} \]</p>
              </div>
              <p>
                Each payment is split between interest and principal. Interest
                for a period is the current balance times \( r \); the rest of
                the payment reduces the balance.
              </p>

              <h3>Simple interest option (no compounding)</h3>
              <p>
                If you enable “Use simple interest”, the calculator assumes
                interest is calculated on the original principal only, not on
                the declining balance. Total interest is:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p>\[ \text{Total Interest} = P \times R \times T \]</p>
                <p>where:</p>
                <ul>
                  <li>\( P \) = principal</li>
                  <li>\( R \) = annual interest rate (as a decimal)</li>
                  <li>\( T \) = term in years</li>
                </ul>
                <p>The payment per period is then:</p>
                <p>\[ A = \frac{P + \text{Total Interest}}{n} \]</p>
              </div>

              <h3>Using extra payments to pay off faster</h3>
              <p>
                The “Extra payment per period” field lets you simulate paying
                more than the required amount. The calculator applies the extra
                directly to principal each period, which:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>Reduces the number of payments</li>
                <li>Cuts total interest</li>
                <li>Shortens the payoff time</li>
              </ul>

              <h2>FAQ</h2>

              <h3>What is a simple loan?</h3>
              <p>
                A simple loan is a fixed-rate installment loan with regular
                payments over a set term. Examples include personal loans, auto
                loans, and many debt consolidation loans.
              </p>

              <h3>Is this the same as a simple interest loan?</h3>
              <p>
                Not always. Many lenders use amortizing interest (interest on
                the remaining balance). This calculator supports both standard
                amortizing loans and pure simple-interest loans via the toggle.
              </p>

              <h3>Does this calculator include fees?</h3>
              <p>
                No. Origination fees, late fees, and other charges are not
                included. To approximate the effect of an upfront fee, you can
                reduce the “Loan amount” by the fee amount or compare scenarios.
              </p>

              <h3>Is this financial advice?</h3>
              <p>
                No. This tool is for education and planning only. Always review
                actual loan offers and consult a qualified professional before
                making borrowing decisions.
              </p>
